article.headline: While Sol miss Riley, Lynx get jolt from Smith
article.linkText: Smith makes debut for Lynx, who top Sol in OT
article.story:
MIAMI (AP) -- Svetlana Abrosimova scored 14 of her 21 points in the second half, and Katie Smith added 18 in her season debut as the Minnesota Lynx held off the Miami Sol 66-63 on Tuesday night. Smith, the WNBA's scoring leader last season, missed Minnesota's loss to Utah on Saturday because of a dislocated and cut right index finger. She showed no ill effects despite playing with seven stitches, shooting 5-of-7 from the field, including 3-for-4 from 3-point range. Rookie Tamara Moore, Miami's first-round pick in the 2002 draft, scored 22 points, but missed a potential game-tying 3-pointer with 0.3 seconds remaining. Minnesota (1-1), which had lost 18 straight when trailing at halftime since the start of the 2001 season, won despite commiting 23 turnovers. The Sol played without center Ruth Riley, who will miss at least four weeks with a broken finger. Miami led 31-30 at halftime, but missed 17 of its first 19 second-half shots and fell behind 49-40 with 8:03 left. A 10-2 Miami run drew the Sol within 51-50 with 5:19 remaining, but the Sol would never reclaim the lead. Miami had plenty of chances to challenge Minnesota in the final minutes, but the turning point came on a mental mistake by the Sol's Sheri Sam with 25 seconds remaining. Sam intercepted a pass by Smith and was all alone on a drive to the basket, but missed an easy layup that would have cut Minnesota's lead to one. Georgia Schweitzer grabbed the rebound, was fouled and made one free throw with 22.1 seconds remaining, putting the Lynx ahead 65-61. Abrosimova, who has 47 points in Minnesota's first two games, made all three of her 3-point tries and was 8-for-13 from the field. Minnesota scored the first eight points of the game, but Miami rallied and took its biggest first-half lead with 2:30 remaining, when Moore scored to put the Sol ahead 29-24. Smith hit a long 3-pointer as the halftime buzzer sounded, cutting the Sol lead to 31-30 at intermission.

Game notes
Minnesota improved to 4-0 all-time against the Sol. ... Miami fell to 1-2 in season-opening games, all three of which have been on its home floor. ... Since the beginning of the 2001 season, the Sol are 5-8 in games that Riley did not start. ... Miami plays host to Los Angeles (2-0) on Thursday night. The Sparks are 2-0 against the Sol all-time, including an 86-60 victory last July 1.
